{
  "schema_name": "eywa_node_response",
  "schema_version": "v1",
  "orchestration_decision": "delegate",
  "decision_notes": "The problem is a combinatorial optimization problem involving a 9x9 grid and 3x3 stamp placements. I have decomposed it into data extraction, mathematical modeling of the objective function, and an optimization strategy.",
  "helpers": [
    {
      "label": "helper_1",
      "instructions": "Extract all numerical parameters and constraints from the problem text. Specifically, identify the board dimensions, the stamp dimensions, the maximum number of placements K, and the modulus value. Note that the board entries are not explicitly provided in the text, so flag this as a requirement for the input data."
    },
    {
      "label": "helper_2",
      "instructions": "Formulate the mathematical model for the objective function. Define the board as a 9x9 matrix. Define a placement as a top-left coordinate (r, c) for a 3x3 stamp. Express the total sum as the sum of all cells in the board after applying up to K stamps. Since the problem asks to maximize the sum modulo 998244353, clarify if the modulo applies to the final sum or if the sum is calculated within the field. Note: In standard competitive programming, this usually means maximizing the sum and then taking the modulo, but the phrasing suggests the sum itself is the target."
    },
    {
      "label": "helper_3",
      "instructions": "Develop an algorithmic approach to solve the optimization. Given the small board size (9x9) and K=81, evaluate whether a greedy approach, dynamic programming, or exhaustive search/backtracking is feasible. Since K=81 is the maximum possible number of 3x3 stamps on a 9x9 board (if overlapping is allowed and every cell is covered), determine if the optimal strategy is simply to place stamps on all possible positions or if there is a specific selection process required."
    }
  ],
  "synthesis_brief": "Combine the extracted parameters, the mathematical objective function, and the algorithmic strategy to calculate the maximum possible sum of the board entries under the given constraints, applying the modulo at the final step."
}

